## Summary

`%Error-DIDNOTCONVERGE: NBA region did not converge` when two class instances each hold a `virtual` reference to a **different instance** of the **same interface type**, and a module connects them via `always_ff` with a combinational output path.

PR #6148 fixed the ICO-region variant of #5116 by adding per-member triggers. This issue is the NBA-region variant — the NBA triggers still appear to use one trigger per virtual interface **type**, so a DUT writing to instance B re-triggers NBA evaluation of instance A (held by a different class), creating an infinite loop.

## Minimal reproducer

```systemverilog
`timescale 1ns/1ps

interface stream_if (input logic clk);
    logic       valid;
    logic       ready;
    logic [7:0] data;

    clocking cb @(posedge clk);
        default input #1step output #0;
        output valid, data;
        input  ready;
    endclocking
endinterface

class source_driver;
    virtual stream_if vif;

    function new(virtual stream_if vif);
        this.vif = vif;
    endfunction

    task run();
        vif.cb.valid <= 1'b0;
        vif.cb.data  <= '0;
        @(vif.cb);
        vif.cb.valid <= 1'b1;
        vif.cb.data  <= 8'hAB;
        do @(vif.cb);
        while (!(vif.valid && vif.cb.ready));
        vif.cb.valid <= 1'b0;
        @(vif.cb);
    endtask
endclass

class sink_driver;
    virtual stream_if vif;

    function new(virtual stream_if vif);
        this.vif = vif;
    endfunction

    task run();
        vif.ready = 1'b1;
        forever @(posedge vif.clk);
    endtask
endclass

module pipe (
    input  logic       clk,
    input  logic       s_valid,
    output logic       s_ready,
    input  logic [7:0] s_data,
    output logic       m_valid,
    input  logic       m_ready,
    output logic [7:0] m_data
);
    assign s_ready = !m_valid || m_ready;

    always_ff @(posedge clk) begin
        if (s_ready) begin
            m_valid <= s_valid;
            m_data  <= s_data;
        end
    end
endmodule

module top;
    logic clk = 0;
    always #5 clk = ~clk;

    stream_if a (.clk(clk));
    stream_if b (.clk(clk));

    pipe dut (
        .clk     (clk),
        .s_valid (a.valid),
        .s_ready (a.ready),
        .s_data  (a.data),
        .m_valid (b.valid),
        .m_ready (b.ready),
        .m_data  (b.data)
    );

    source_driver src;
    sink_driver   snk;

    initial begin
        src = new(a);
        snk = new(b);
        fork
            src.run();
            snk.run();
        join_any
        #50;
        $display("PASS");
        $finish;
    end
endmodule
```

## Build & run

```
verilator --binary --timing -sv nba_vif_bug.sv -Wno-fatal
./obj_dir/Vnba_vif_bug
```

## Observed

```
%Error-DIDNOTCONVERGE: nba_vif_bug.sv:82: NBA region did not converge after '--converge-limit' of 100 tries
```

## Expected

```
PASS
```

## Key observations

- Removing **either** class (so only one virtual reference exists) → PASS
- Removing the `clocking cb` block → PASS  
- Using two **different** interface types (one per instance) → PASS
- The ICO-region fix from PR #6148 is present in this build (`7c923bb`, master as of 2026-02-23)

## Analysis

The NBA scheduling trigger appears to still be per virtual interface **type** rather than per member or per instance. When the `pipe` module's `always_ff` NBA updates `m_valid` → combinational `s_ready` change → writes to instance `a.ready` and `b.valid` via port connections → fires the `stream_if` NBA trigger → re-evaluates `source_driver`'s virtual reference to instance `a` → spurious NBA re-scheduling → infinite loop.

## Version

```
Verilator 5.045 devel rev 7c923bb (master, includes PR #6148)
```

